{
  "The primary energy source driving the water cycle is:": "",
  "Gravity": "",
  "Solar energy": "",
  "Geothermal heat": "",
  "Wind": "",
  "The Sun provides the energy that drives evaporation from oceans, lakes, and other water bodies, which is the fundamental process that moves water from the surface into the atmosphere and powers the entire hydrologic cycle.": "",
  "Approximately what percentage of Earth's water is saltwater?": "",
  "50%": "",
  "75%": "",
  "100%": "",
  "97.5%": "",
  "About 97.5% of all water on Earth is saltwater in the oceans, leaving only 2.5% as freshwater, and most of that freshwater is locked in glaciers and ice caps, making less than 1% of all water readily accessible for human use.": "",
  "Most of Earth's freshwater is found in:": "",
  "Glaciers and ice caps": "",
  "Rivers and lakes": "",
  "Underground aquifers": "",
  "The atmosphere": "",
  "Approximately 68.7% of Earth's freshwater is stored in glaciers and ice caps, primarily in Antarctica and Greenland, making them by far the largest freshwater reservoirs, followed by groundwater at about 30%.": "",
  "Evaporation occurs when water changes from:": "",
  "Gas to liquid": "",
  "Liquid to gas": "",
  "Gas to solid": "",
  "Solid to liquid": "",
  "Evaporation is the process by which liquid water absorbs energy and transforms into water vapor (gas), occurring primarily at the surface of oceans, lakes, rivers, and moist soil, and it is the main mechanism by which water enters the atmosphere.": "",
  "Condensation in the atmosphere forms:": "",
  "Clouds and fog": "",
  "Glaciers": "",
  "Groundwater": "",
  "Rivers and streams": "",
  "Condensation occurs when water vapor cools to the dew point and changes back into tiny liquid droplets or ice crystals on condensation nuclei, forming visible clouds and fog in the atmosphere.": "",
  "Water that soaks into the ground rather than flowing over the surface is undergoing:": "",
  "Infiltration": "",
  "Transpiration": "",
  "Evaporation": "",
  "Condensation": "",
  "Infiltration is the process by which water on the ground surface enters the soil, percolating downward through pore spaces to recharge groundwater supplies, and the rate depends on soil type, vegetation cover, and how saturated the soil already is.": "",
  "Transpiration is the process by which water:": "",
  "Flows over the ground surface as runoff": "",
  "Seeps into underground aquifers": "",
  "Evaporates from plant leaves into the atmosphere": "",
  "Freezes into ice in clouds": "",
  "Transpiration occurs when plants absorb water through their roots and release it as water vapor through tiny pores (stomata) in their leaves, accounting for a significant portion of water returned to the atmosphere, especially in forested areas.": "",
  "Surface runoff occurs when:": "",
  "Clouds release moisture as precipitation": "",
  "Water evaporates from the ocean surface": "",
  "Rainfall exceeds the soil's ability to absorb it, causing water to flow over the surface": "",
  "Groundwater rises to the surface through springs": "",
  "Surface runoff occurs when precipitation rate exceeds the infiltration rate of the soil, or when the soil is already saturated, causing excess water to flow downhill over the surface toward streams, rivers, and eventually the ocean.": "",
  "Sublimation is the process by which water changes from:": "",
  "Liquid to solid, particularly regarding regions": "",
  "Liquid to gas, particularly regarding without": "",
  "Solid directly to gas without passing through the liquid phase": "",
  "Gas to liquid, particularly regarding directly": "",
  "Sublimation occurs when ice or snow transitions directly into water vapor without first melting into liquid water, a process that occurs under conditions of low humidity and strong sunlight, and is important for snow and ice loss in dry mountainous regions.": "",
  "The oceans are the largest source of atmospheric water vapor because they cover approximately _____ of Earth's surface.": "",
  "71%": "",
  "90%": "",
  "60%": "",
  "Oceans cover approximately 71% of Earth's surface, providing the vast majority of the water that evaporates into the atmosphere, with about 86% of global evaporation occurring from ocean surfaces.": "",
  "What is the hydrologic (water) cycle?": "",
  "The continuous movement of water through evaporation, condensation, precipitation, and collection as it cycles between the atmosphere, land, and oceans": "",
  "The process by which water treatment plants clean drinking water": "",
  "The one-way flow of water from mountains to the ocean": "",
  "The seasonal pattern of rainfall in tropical regions": "",
  "The hydrologic cycle is the continuous, natural process by which water circulates through the Earth system, moving between the oceans, atmosphere, and land through evaporation, condensation, precipitation, infiltration, runoff, and transpiration.": "",
  "What is evapotranspiration?": "",
  "The process of water freezing and thawing in soil": "",
  "The condensation of water vapor onto plant surfaces": "",
  "The movement of groundwater through underground rock layers": "",
  "The combined total of evaporation from surfaces and transpiration from plants returning water to the atmosphere": "",
  "Evapotranspiration combines evaporation (from soil, water surfaces, and wet vegetation) with transpiration (water released by plants through stomata), representing the total water returned to the atmosphere from a given area and a major component of the water budget.": "",
  "What is groundwater recharge?": "",
  "The pumping of water from underground wells for human use": "",
  "The process by which surface water infiltrates the soil and percolates downward to replenish underground water supplies": "",
  "The heating of groundwater by geothermal energy": "",
  "The flow of underground rivers to the ocean": "",
  "Groundwater recharge occurs when precipitation infiltrates the soil and percolates through permeable rock layers to reach the water table, replenishing aquifers, and the rate of recharge depends on soil permeability, land cover, precipitation amount, and topography.": "",
  "What is a water table?": "",
  "A table used to display water samples in a laboratory": "",
  "A dam built to store water in a reservoir": "",
  "The upper surface of the zone of saturation where all pore spaces in rock and soil are completely filled with water": "",
  "The surface of a lake or pond": "",
  "The water table is the boundary between the unsaturated zone (where pore spaces contain both air and water) above and the saturated zone (where all pore spaces are completely filled with water) below, and its depth varies with precipitation, season, and pumping activity.": "",
  "What is the residence time of water?": "",
  "The average amount of time a water molecule spends in a particular reservoir before moving to another part of the hydrologic cycle": "",
  "The time it takes for a raindrop to fall from a cloud to the ground": "",
  "The length of time water is stored in a water treatment facility": "",
  "The number of days between rain events in a region": "",
  "Residence time varies enormously among different reservoirs: water vapor stays in the atmosphere for about 9 days, river water for about 2 weeks, but water in the deep ocean can remain for over 1,000 years and in glaciers for tens of thousands of years.": "",
  "What is precipitation?": "",
  "The absorption of water by plant roots": "",
  "The underground movement of water through rock formations": "",
  "Water in any form (rain, snow, sleet, hail) that falls from clouds to Earth's surface": "",
  "The process of water vapor rising into the atmosphere": "",
  "Precipitation includes all forms of water that fall from the atmosphere to Earth's surface, including rain, snow, sleet, hail, and freezing rain, and it is the primary mechanism by which water returns from the atmosphere to the surface.": "",
  "What is a drainage basin?": "",
  "The entire land area from which water drains into a particular river, lake, or ocean": "",
  "The bottom of a river channel": "",
  "A man-made reservoir used for irrigation": "",
  "A depression in the ground where rainwater collects temporarily": "",
  "A drainage basin (also called a watershed or catchment) is the total land area from which all precipitation drains into a common outlet such as a river, lake, or ocean, with the boundaries defined by ridges and divides that separate adjacent basins.": "",
  "What is percolation?": "",
  "The horizontal flow of water in rivers": "",
  "The evaporation of water from leaf surfaces": "",
  "The downward movement of water through soil and rock due to gravity": "",
  "The condensation of water vapor in the atmosphere": "",
  "Percolation is the downward movement of water through the pores and spaces in soil and rock under the influence of gravity, carrying water from the surface through the unsaturated zone to eventually reach the water table and recharge groundwater supplies.": "",
  "What is the water budget of a region?": "",
  "The amount of water a household uses per month": "",
  "The cost of water treatment and distribution in a municipality": "",
  "The total volume of water stored in a region's reservoirs": "",
  "The balance of water inputs (precipitation) and outputs (evapotranspiration, runoff, infiltration) for a specific area": "",
  "A water budget accounts for all water entering and leaving a specific area, balancing inputs like precipitation against outputs like evapotranspiration, surface runoff, and groundwater flow, helping hydrologists understand water availability.": "",
  "What is latent heat in the water cycle?": "",
  "The temperature of underground water in deep wells": "",
  "The energy absorbed or released when water changes phase (such as from liquid to vapor or vapor to liquid) without changing temperature": "",
  "The heat generated by friction as water flows through pipes": "",
  "The heat stored in ocean water due to solar radiation": "",
  "Latent heat is the energy absorbed during evaporation and released during condensation without changing the water's temperature, and it plays a critical role in redistributing energy through the atmosphere, powering storms and transferring heat from tropical oceans to higher latitudes.": "",
  "A farmer in a semi-arid region notices that after clearing native vegetation to plant crops, the local streams flood more frequently during rain events and dry up faster between rains. This occurs because:": "",
  "The cleared land reflects more sunlight, reducing local evaporation": "",
  "Crops attract more rainfall than native vegetation": "",
  "Removing vegetation reduces infiltration and transpiration, causing more rapid surface runoff during rain and less groundwater recharge to sustain stream baseflow between rains": "",
  "Native plants were blocking the streams and causing flooding": "",
  "Native vegetation slows runoff, promotes infiltration, and returns water to the atmosphere through transpiration; removing it increases surface runoff (causing flash flooding) while reducing groundwater recharge that would have sustained stream flow during dry periods.": "",
  "A city experiences severe flooding during heavy rainstorms even though nearby rural areas with the same rainfall do not flood. The primary reason is that:": "",
  "Impervious surfaces like roads, buildings, and parking lots prevent infiltration, converting nearly all rainfall into rapid surface runoff": "",
  "Urban heat islands cause more intense rainfall within city limits": "",
  "Cities are located at lower elevations than surrounding rural areas": "",
  "City drainage systems deliberately flood streets to wash them clean": "",
  "In natural landscapes, 10-20% of rainfall becomes runoff, but in heavily urbanized areas with extensive impervious surfaces, up to 55% or more becomes rapid runoff because water cannot infiltrate through concrete and asphalt, overwhelming drainage systems.": "",
  "Climate scientists observe that as global temperatures rise, the water cycle is intensifying. This means that:": "",
  "Evaporation rates are increasing, leading to more atmospheric moisture, heavier precipitation events, and more extreme droughts between rain events": "",
  "All regions of the world are receiving more rainfall equally": "",
  "Total water on Earth is increasing due to warming": "",
  "The water cycle is slowing down due to higher temperatures": "",
  "Warmer temperatures increase evaporation rates and the atmosphere's capacity to hold moisture (about 7% more per degree Celsius), intensifying the water cycle so that when it does rain, precipitation is often heavier, while evaporation also increases drought severity between rain events.": "",
  "A mountain community depends on spring snowmelt for its summer water supply. If climate change causes more winter precipitation to fall as rain instead of snow, the community would face:": "",
  "Better water quality because rain is purer than snowmelt": "",
  "More water available year-round since rain runs off immediately": "",
  "Increased winter flooding from rapid runoff and summer water shortages due to reduced snowpack that would normally melt slowly and provide water during dry months": "",
  "No change because the total precipitation amount remains the same": "",
  "Snowpack acts as a natural reservoir, storing water in winter and releasing it slowly as melt during spring and summer when demand is highest; shifting from snow to rain removes this storage function, causing more immediate winter runoff and leaving less water available during critical summer months.": "",
  "After a major wildfire destroys all vegetation on a hillside, the area experiences severe mudslides during the first heavy rain. This happens because:": "",
  "The fire heated the soil, making it expand and become unstable": "",
  "Wildfires release chemicals that attract more rainfall": "",
  "The burned area creates a low-pressure zone that pulls in storms": "",
  "Without vegetation to intercept rain, slow runoff, and hold soil with roots, water runs off rapidly carrying loose sediment and ash downslope": "",
  "Wildfire destroys the vegetation canopy that intercepts rainfall, the litter layer that slows surface flow, and the root networks that stabilize soil, and it can also create a water-repellent layer in the soil, dramatically increasing runoff and erosion.": "",
  "A hydrologist studying water resources discovers that a region's groundwater levels have been declining steadily for decades. The most likely explanation is that:": "",
  "The water table naturally drops over time regardless of human activity": "",
  "Water is being pumped out of aquifers for irrigation and human use faster than natural recharge from precipitation can replace it": "",
  "Increased vegetation is absorbing all the underground water through roots": "",
  "Underground earthquakes have created new channels draining the aquifer": "",
  "When groundwater extraction exceeds the rate of natural recharge from precipitation infiltration, aquifer levels decline over time, a process called groundwater depletion, which threatens long-term water security for agriculture and communities that depend on wells.": "",
  "Tropical rainforests contribute significantly to the water cycle through transpiration. If large areas of the Amazon rainforest are deforested, the most likely regional impact would be:": "",
  "Increased rainfall because fewer trees means less water is used by plants": "",
  "No change in rainfall because the ocean provides all atmospheric moisture": "",
  "Reduced regional rainfall because transpiration from the forest provides a large portion of the moisture that becomes local precipitation": "",
  "Increased snowfall in the deforested areas": "",
  "In the Amazon, a significant portion of rainfall is recycled water: trees transpire moisture that forms clouds and falls again as rain further inland, so large-scale deforestation could reduce this moisture recycling and lead to significantly less rainfall in the region.": "",
  "A coastal city plans to use desalination to supplement its water supply during droughts. While desalination can provide freshwater from the ocean, an important consideration is that:": "",
  "The process requires significant energy and produces concentrated brine waste that must be managed to avoid harming marine ecosystems": "",
  "Desalination removes all water from the ocean, depleting it over time": "",
  "Desalination only works in tropical climates": "",
  "Desalinated water is not safe for human consumption": "",
  "Desalination is energy-intensive and expensive, and it produces concentrated brine (water with very high salt content) that, if discharged improperly, can harm marine organisms in the discharge area, making energy costs and environmental management key considerations.": "",
  "During a warm, humid day, water droplets form on the outside of a glass of ice water. This everyday example demonstrates the water cycle process of:": "",
  "Infiltration, because water is seeping through the glass walls": "",
  "Condensation, because the cold glass cools the surrounding moist air below its dew point, causing water vapor to condense on the surface": "",
  "Precipitation, because water is falling from the atmosphere onto the glass": "",
  "Evaporation, because the cold glass causes water to evaporate from the ice": "",
  "The cold glass surface cools the thin layer of air in contact with it below the dew point temperature, causing water vapor in that air to condense into visible liquid droplets on the glass, exactly the same process that forms clouds when air cools at altitude.": "",
  "A research team measures that a lake receives 500 million liters of water per year from precipitation and streams but loses 600 million liters per year to evaporation and outflow. If no other inputs exist, the lake will:": "",
  "Freeze because the water deficit causes temperatures to drop": "",
  "Overflow because more water enters than leaves": "",
  "Remain at the same level because the water cycle always balances": "",
  "Slowly shrink because its outputs exceed its inputs by 100 million liters per year, creating a negative water budget": "",
  "When a lake's water outputs (evaporation plus outflow) exceed its inputs (precipitation plus inflow), the lake has a negative water budget and will shrink over time, as has been observed in many lakes worldwide where climate change or water diversion has altered the balance.": ""
}